A '''bright-line rule''' is a clear-cut, easy to make decision. 

In policy debate, it is a topicality standard which argues that the definition is black and white, that one can easily tell whether or not a specific circumstance meets the definition.

In law a bright-line rule, or bright-line test, is a legal precident which is easy to apply and find how a judge will rule.  Bright-line rules are often contrasted with "squishy" [[balancing test|balancing tests]].  There is a sharp division over the validity and use of one in preference for the other.
